observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the implementing Department Heads: 

Retrieve all MOA or any related documents to determine the specific purpose of each fund received from the National Agencies; 
Implement the programs, projects and activities for the intended purpose within the timelines agreed; and

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor monitor the timely implementation of all programs, projects and activities funded by the National Agencies, as stated and agreed in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA).

We further recommended that the Municipal Treasurer: 

Retain a copy of the MOA on all funds received from any Source Agencies;

Return all unexpended balance or excess funds to the source agency; and

Return all idle funds with the Bureau of Treasury for those funds with undeterminable Source Agency and/or its specific purpose, only after all efforts and remedies are exhausted.

Finally, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, exhaust all efforts and remedies to determine the specific details on the unsubstantiated balances of the Due to NGA account;

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:

Update the Taxpayer’s Index Card and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Assessors;
Submit the Taxpayer’s Index Card to the Municipal Accountant at the start of each year as the basis in recognition of the RPT Receivables;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

pay the mandated daily minimum wage prescribed by the RTWPB for Region VIII;

reduce the number of Job Order personnel in the LGU to those which are considered essential and urgent;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a)	create an Inventory Committee composed of adequate members, with at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Office;

b)	require the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all properties of the LGU every year and prepare a completely filled out RPCPPE, grouped per account for easy monitoring and reconciliation 
and submit the same to the Auditor no later than January 31 of each year;

c)	consider appointing a Supply Officer to oversee management of PPE of the Municipality.

Moreover, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer reconcile their records in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 (One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balance) to ensure an accurate and reliable PPE balance by year-end.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant/Personnel-in-Charge:

a)	ensure that all withheld taxes are fully remitted to the BIR in the immediately succeeding month, as required by tax regulations.  Late remittances should be avoided to prevent penalties and surcharges;

b)	regularly check that the amounts withheld match payroll records, supplier payments, and other taxable transactions to ensure accuracy before remittance;

c)	conduct a monthly review and reconciliation between the withholding tax records and the general ledger before remitting to the BIR to detect and correct any discrepancies and confirm that all withholding tax obligations are properly accounted for and reflected in the financial reports; and

d)	maintain separate subsidiary ledger accounts for different types of withholding taxes such as compensation, expanded withholding tax, and VAT.

We recommended that the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO):

a)	ensure that all salary deductions are correctly computed and recorded before payroll processing and coordinate with Accounting to reconcile payroll deductions with actual remittances; and 

b)	maintain accurate and updated employee records to prevent erroneous deductions or missing remittances.

We also recommended that the Agency Authorized Officer (AAO):

a)	ensure all withheld contributions are remitted within the prescribed deadlines to avoid penalties and interest charges; 

b)	ensure that the total amount remitted matches with the actual premiums, loan amortizations, and MP2 savings withheld from employees’ salaries, including the government’s share; 

c)	maintain accurate and complete records of payroll deductions, remittance reports, and official receipts; and

d)	coordinate with HDMF to reconcile any billing discrepancies and request adjustments when necessary and ensure proper posting of payments.

Finally, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

a)	conduct a reconciliation of payroll deductions and remittances using payroll records, remittance reports, and HDMF billings to identify the source of discrepancies; 

b)	identify and recover any excess remittances made for employees whose salaries were not withheld; 

c)	immediately remit any shortfall in HDMF contributions and loan payments to prevent delays, penalties, or benefit disruptions; and

d)	maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for the Due to HDMF account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the Human Resource Management Officer ensure that travel allowances are paid only to JO personnel whose contracts explicitly authorize travel;

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue an Executive Order establishing internal policies, guidelines, and limitations on travel claims for JO personnel; and

Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the travel claims of JO personnel to ensure they are properly approved by the authorized official and supported by the required certifications and other necessary documents before processing payment.

