We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue an Executive Order establishing internal policies, guidelines, and limitations on travel claims for JO personnel; and
Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the travel claims of JO personnel to ensure they are properly approved by the authorized official and supported by the required certifications and other necessary documents before processing payment.

We recommended that the Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count of all properties of the LGU every year and prepare a completely filled out RPCPPE, grouped per account for easy monitoring and reconciliation and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer reconcile their records in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 (One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balance) to ensure an accurate and reliable PPE balance by year-end.
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant derecognize the Semi-Expendable Properties totaling ₱5,187,248.82 from the PPE account through the account Prior Period Adjustment and close the corresponding accumulated depreciation and accumulated impairment losses in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO) or the Agency Authorized Officer:
Identify and recover any excess or deficient collections/remittances made for employees, including the remitted amount of ₱542,141.43 for salaries that were not withheld, and request a refund, if necessary;
Reconcile records with GSIS and promptly communicate any necessary updates regarding employees’ employment status to ensure that GSIS records are accurately maintained in a timely manner;
Ensure that all premium contributions and loan amortizations are deducted from employees’ salaries in the payroll for the month they are due;
Verify that payroll deductions align with actual employee contributions and loan amortizations before processing remittances;
Ensure that all premium contributions and loan amortizations are remitted within the prescribed deadlines to avoid penalties and interest charges; and
Conduct monthly reconciliations of employee premium contributions and loan amortizations by comparing GSIS billing records with actual payroll deductions and remitted amounts. This ensures billing accuracy, facilitates timely remittances, and guarantees correct salary deductions.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Remit any deficiencies in GSIS premium contributions and loan amortizations after thorough verification to prevent delays, penalties, or disruptions in employee benefits;
Maintain updated Subsidiary Ledgers for the "Due to GSIS" account to ensure accurate deductions, remittances, and employee benefit entitlements; and
Reconcile the remitted amount of ₱542,141.43 with the HRMO based on payroll records to confirm that the corresponding Personal Share (PS) amounts were properly deducted from the salaries of LGU employees.
Lastly, we recommended that the Municipal Budget Officer refrain from approving expenditures that are not supported by sufficient appropriations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor secure a corresponding Sanggunian Bayan (SB) Resolution authorizing the execution of contracts and the hiring of Job Order (JO) personnel;
We also reiterated the previous recommendation that the Municipal Mayor, in consultation with the Municipal Budget Officer, adopt the prevailing minimum daily wage for Job Order personnel, as prescribed under the updated Wage Order Regional Board by the DOLE-RTWPB.
Further, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the Human Resource Management Officer:
Develop and issue written policy guidelines that outlines the standard procedures of hiring Job Order (JO) personnel to ensure the objective and impartial selection process, which specifies the required documents to be submitted by applicants, the detailed job description in the Contract of Service, the submission of accomplishment reports by JO personnel, and other necessary internal control measures. This will streamline the hiring process and promote transparency and accountability;
Conduct a comprehensive assessment and evaluation of the current manpower complement to identify and remove any redundant or unnecessary Job Order (JO) workers who performs tasks and responsibilities that were covered already by other staff or regular plantilla personnel; and
Lastly, we recommended that the LGU limit the hiring of Job Order personnel for essential tasks that complements and supports the existing workforce of the LGU, thereby optimizing operational efficiency.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the Human Resource Management Officer ensure that payments of travel allowance are made only to JO personnel whose contracts explicitly authorize travel;
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue an Executive Order establishing clear internal policies, guidelines, and limitations on travel claims for JO personnel; and
Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant conduct a thorough review of JO personnel's travel claims to ensure that they are properly approved by the authorized official and supported by the required certifications and necessary documents before processing payment.

We recommended that the Local School Board develop a three-year program outlining strategic prioritization policies for allocating the SEF among schools within the municipality;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer submit the following certified statement to the LSB not later than July 15 of the current year, to wit
Actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year;
Actual SEF Income for the first two quarters of the current year;
Estimated SEF Income for the last two quarters of the current year; and
Annual Estimates for the ensuing year;
We further recommended that the LSB review and approve the SEF Budget for the ensuing year no later than October 31 of the current year to ensure timely and effective planning and budgeting of the SEF;
Lastly, we recommended that the Local School Board and the Municipal Accountant diligently comply with the reportorial requirements in the allocation and utilization on Special Education Fund as outlined in the afore-cited regulations.

