Lastly, we recommended that the Local School Board and the Municipal Accountant diligently comply with the reportorial requirements in the allocation and utilization on Special Education Fund as outlined in the afore-cited regulations.
During the Exit Conference, the Local School Board (LSB) Secretary explained that they were not aware of the deadline for the preparation of the SEF Budget. Nevertheless, she agreed to the recommendations and committed to prepare the SEF Budget for CY 2026 no later that October 31 of the current year.
The Municipal Accountant and LSB Secretary both agreed to the other recommendations.
The Municipal Treasurer did not give his comments to the recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor obtain a corresponding Sanggunian Bayan (SB) Resolution that authorizes to enter into a contract and hires Job Order (JO) personnel;
We reiterated the previous recommendation that the Municipal Mayor, in consultation with the Municipal Budget Officer and the Human Resource Management Officer, adopt the prevailing minimum daily wage for Job Order personnel, as prescribed under the updated Wage Order Regional Board by the DOLE-RTWPB.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor and the Human Resource Management Officer:
Develop and issue written policy guidelines that outlines the standard procedures of hiring Job Order (JO) personnel to ensure the objective and impartial selection process, which specifies the required documents to be submitted by applicants, the detailed job description in the Contract of Service/Job Order Contract, the submission of accomplishment reports by JO personnel, time of payment of their wages and other necessary internal control measures. This will streamline the hiring process and promote transparency and accountability;
Conduct a comprehensive assessment and evaluation of the current manpower complement to identify and remove any redundant or unnecessary Job Order (JO) workers who performs tasks and responsibilities that were covered already by other staff or regular plantilla personnel;
Limit the hiring of Job Order personnel for essential tasks that complements and supports the existing workforce of the LGU, thereby optimizing operational efficiency; and,
Require the 131 personnel JO workers to appear before the Audit Team for head count and verification purposes.
During the Exit Conference, the officials and employees present collectively agreed to comply with the recommendations. They also agreed to require the Job Order personnel to appear before the Audit Team via Zoom Conference the day after the exit conference.

We recommended that the concerned Accountable Officers immediately submit, within 30 days from receipt of the AOM, the liquidation reports and the supporting documents, otherwise, restitute/return immediately the amount equivalent to their respective unliquidated cash advances, if warranted.
We reiterated our previous recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:
Discontinue the grant of cash advances to officials and employees with outstanding cash advances;
Require the accountable officers, especially those with long overdue cash advances, and those outgoing elected officials and employees before issuing their certificates of clearance, to immediately settle or refund their unliquidated cash advance; and
Issue a directive to the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the salaries of officials and employees who failed to liquidate their cash advances, based on the recommendations of the Municipal Accountant;
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Regularly demand from the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances, the immediate settlement, refund or submission of liquidation reports on cash advances where the purposes have already been served;
Recommend to the Municipal Mayor the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who continue to fail to submit their Liquidation Reports within the period prescribed by regulations;
Discontinue the processing DVs for grants of additional cash advance to officials and employees with previous unliquidated cash advances to avoid accumulation thereof.
Finally, we recommended that the Municipal Treasurer withhold the salaries of officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances, if appropriate and warranted, as directed by the Municipal Mayor.
During the Exit Conference, the Municipal Accountant commented that most of the cash advances granted in CY 2024 were already liquidated in CY 2025. She further expressed the difficulties encountered in requiring the employees concerned to liquidated their long outstanding cash advances.
Nevertheless, the Municipal Accountant and other officials and employees present agreed to comply with the recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor monitor the complete implementation of all programs, projects and activities funded by the National Agencies, as stated and agreed in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA).

We recommended that the implementing Department Heads: 

Retrieve all MOA or any related documents to determine the specific purpose of each fund received from the National Agencies; 

Implement the programs, projects and activities for the intended purpose within the timelines agreed; 
Request for counterpart fund as required in the MOA for the implementation thereof;

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Exhaust all efforts and remedies to determine the specific details on the balances of the Due to NGA account; and,

We further recommended that the Municipal Treasurer: 

Return all unexpended balance or excess funds to the source agency; and,

Return all idle funds with the Bureau of Treasury for those funds with undeterminable Source Agency and/or its specific purpose, only after all efforts and remedies are exhausted.

We also recommended that the BAC and its Secretariat: 
Submit written justifications on the noted deficiencies; 

Follow strictly the provisions in the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to avoid legal sanctions;

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Review the correctness of the utilization report prepared by the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer to avoid any inaccurate disclosure of unexpended LDRRM Fund;

Record the unexpended balance of LDRRMF from current year appropriation before the calendar period ends, including the proper disclosure thereof in the Notes to Financial Statements; and

Review the prior year recognition to ascertain the correctness of the unexpended balances of LDRRMF for each year and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct amount;

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer maintain a separate Subsidiary Ledger and Registry, respectively, on the transfer of unutilized DRRMF to the Special Trust Fund per year of transfer, for proper monitoring of the fund, including the yearly reconciliation thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Send demand letters to concerned NGOs/Pos for liquidation;
Disqualify the concerned NGOs/Pos with unliquidated fund transfers for new fund transfers until their previous fund transfers are liquidated pursuant to COA Circular No. 2007-001 dated October 25, 2007;
Verify the actual ages of the unliquidated fund transfers and request for authority to write-off if the ages of such fund transfers qualify them as dormant unliquidated fund transfers pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

